<li id="c11">
  <div class="cx" id="cx49893794">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">why would they?</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1201068/49893794#c11?mode=alone;showrate=1#c11">8+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:6841">badger</a>, <a href="/user/uid:97063">ilex</a>, <a href="/user/uid:83303">Leap Year</a>, <a href="/user/uid:219706">judyms9</a>, <a href="/user/uid:150845">SuetheRedWA</a>, <a href="/user/uid:212664">Mentatmark</a>, <a href="/user/uid:272804">BusyinCA</a>, <a href="/user/uid:330318">JerryNA</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>it would be completely arbitrary. Fixed costs + variable costs + profit margin are set into the price of the final product. Labor is a fixed cost bound by minimum wage (or rarely by prevailing regional wages if there are labor shortages).</p>
<p>There is always a risk with increasing prices even by marginal amounts. Higher price may cause lowered demand. The price is set to maximize reward vs. risk.</p>
<p>Increasing the (generally) fixed price of labor will increase the price, but that cost is spread over the number of items sold per hour. However, an individual will earn the additional amount per hour worked. It is not divided at all (excluding taxes). That increases buying power. So more people have more money, that negligible price increase is more than offset by the larger number of people with more money to spend.</p>
<p>That calculation doesn't work forever, of course. We can't just set minimum wage at $100/hour and expect everything to be peachy. We can, however, expect small increases in wages over time to cause some inflation that is more than offset by the increased buying power of low wage workers.<br /></p>

  </div>
