  <div class="ct">
  
<p>What they are thinking about is how to give them less.</p>
<p>It's always that. &nbsp;</p>
<p>Automate and enable more labor per person and reduce the number of persons.</p>
<p>Always.</p>
<p>And the thing that makes it all work is the fear of getting less for our own labor in a classic divide and conquer scenario.</p>
<p>Nobody wants to talk about the fact that we do not value our peers well enough to live a modest life, because when we do that, we either find we need to change how enterprises actually work and what their motives are</p>
<p>, or</p>
<p>we we find that we believe it's OK to screw a lot of us over so a few of us can get the max possible.</p>
<p>Neither is a pretty scenario overall.</p>
<p>There is another wrinkle here and that is risk. &nbsp;When we allow labor to be compensated at a level below what that labor really costs, risk goes down too!</p>
<p>Say we have somebody making sandwiches for $6 / hour, and it's full time. &nbsp;That's not enough to pay for the person to actually live to make the sandwiches!</p>
<p>That person must get help, or live without basic needs being met, both of which are expensive and brutal.</p>
<p>Our lives are divided into thirds. &nbsp;One to sleep, one to be who we are, raise a family, etc... &nbsp;and one to labor.</p>
<p>When we fail to value people properly, we force them to consume all their waking ours just trying to live, essentially forcing them to work to live and live to work with little else being possible.</p>
<p>This kind of labor is a sure thing! &nbsp;It takes the risk out of business, and where there is a sure thing, there is always a crowd looking for their share.</p>
<p>Result? &nbsp;Tons of "sure thing" kinds of jobs out there, because those employers are enjoying a subsidy business, not really having to account for many costs, externalized through the low labor.</p>

