	<ul id="k49896011" class="cm i1">




<li id="c33">
  <div class="cx" id="cx49897529">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Sams Club </span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1201068/49897529#c33?mode=alone;showrate=1#c33">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Sorry, yes the Sam's Club segment does have some membership income but it's not very significant relative to their net income or profits of Walmart (the corporation, not the segment). I was thinking of the Walmart "segment" of Walmart "the corporation", not the Walmart corporation as a whole.</p>
<p>Sam's had about $1.1B income from memberships but this represented only about 5.4% of Walmart's overall operating income. As such, it's <em>relatively</em> insignificant to the company as a whole. However, it is a substantial chunk of Sam's Club's operating income (which is about $1.9B), not too dissimilar to Costco</p>
<p>Sam's Club is a fairly small part of Walmart overall. Sam's Club accounts for only about 12% of the net sales (including domestic and international) and something around 7% of operating income.</p>
<p>Walmart has about 2.2 million employees worldwide -- over ten times that of Costco.</p>
<p>Costco has a revenue of about $99M or about 99/0.174 = $569K/employee. Walmart (including Sam's Club) has a revenue of about $469M or about 469/2.2 = $213K/employee. If we assume that average hours per employee per week at both companies is the same<sup>1</sup>, an constant increase in wages while keeping profits constant would require that Walmart raise prices 569/213 = 2.6 times more than Costco. This, of course, helps Costco and hurts Walmart. In fact, since Costco already pays higher wages, they would probably not have to raise their wages quite as much.</p>
<p>It's in Costco's economic interest to support legislation that hurts their competition more than it hurts them (i.e. "rent seeking"). I suspect that Costco's support for a wage increase may not be quite as pure as it seems at first glance.</p>
<hr width="10%" />
[1] Admittedly a big assumption that I'm pulling out of the air - I'd guess that Walmart employees work less hours per week in reality.<br />

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:48607">WillR</a> on <a href="/comments/1201068/49897529#c33">Sat Apr 13, 2013 at 07:28:58 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c30">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


	<ul id="k49897529" class="cm i1">




<li id="c36">
  <div class="cx" id="cx49898449">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Why argue motives?</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1201068/49898449#c36?mode=alone;showrate=1#c36">1+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:67799">417els</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I don't care why some companies treat their employees well (within the law and certain moral constraints, of course), only that they do so.</p>
<p>Would the extra income for workers be less spendable because Costco's motives don't seem pure to you? It doesn't seem Costco is doing any harm to anyone by advocating the minimum wage. They have no responsibility to make WalMart's shoddy, low employee productivity business model succeed.</p>
<p>And the business press and case study links I can find via google generally say that Jim Sinegal believes employee satisfaction leads to profitability. Costco seems to structure their company on that principle - far beyond just supporting increases in the minimum wage. Do you have some evidence he's being deceitful when he says that? Because when I shop at Costco, the employees generally seem both happy and helpful.</p>
<p>Is it possible that the Costco model aligns employee interests with corporate interests, and isn't that better - a win-win situation - for all of us?</p>
<p>I've never bought into the point of view that all corporate types are greedy and venal. Just most of them. I worked for a company (no longer exists) that had a similar attitude to what Costco's appears to be. I knew the CEO/founder, and he treated employees well because he was a decent guy. He built a $4B/yr company doing that, and there's a major business school named after him.<br /></p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig">
No matter how cynical you become, it's never enough to keep up - Lily Tomlin
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:6841">badger</a> on <a href="/comments/1201068/49898449#c36">Sat Apr 13, 2013 at 10:21:21 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c33">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


	<ul id="k49898449" class="cm i1">




<li id="c37">
  <div class="cx" id="cx49898742">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">You are making this an argument, ...</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1201068/49898742#c37?mode=alone;showrate=1#c37">1+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:35548">Samulayo</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>...not I.</p>
<p>My point was simple, to compare Walmart (the segment consisting of 'non warehouse' Walmart stores - those that most people think of as 'Walmart' instead of as 'Sam's Club') to Costco is like comparing airplanes to railroads -- both sell stuff, but the business model and economics of the two are as unlike as strip mining and nano-technology in spite of both of them moving stuff. I just can't think of a time that I've made a decision to "shop at Walmart or Costco for these items" -- the answer is obvious: If Costco has it in their limited inventory and I need a lot of it, I buy it at Costco, else I'll buy it somewhere else.</p>
<p>Personally, and of course I've only shopped at Costco for twenty plus years and only at maybe eight warehouses routinely, I've not found the employees to be particularly helpful or particularly happy. Generally they seem quite a bit smarter than the minimum wage worker at Walmart. I doubt that Costco would hire most Walmart workers at any price -- i.e., if all stores were Costco, likely wages would be higher and 80% of those that worked at Walmart would be unemployed. I've seen horribly irresponsible behavior by Costco workers just because they couldn't be bothered or had the time/motivation to do the right thing - they are not Gods.</p>
<p>If I had to work retail, personally, I would likely pick Walmart over Costco based on what little I know -- simply because I could become a store manager and regional manager much more quickly at Walmart as the competition for such jobs would be much easier and the rewards greater for the higher levels once one achieves them.</p>
<p>Interesting that the company whose CEO you thought had a similar attitude to Costco's "no longer exists". Without more information, it sounds like that model didn't work so well -- perhaps there's more to it than that.</p>
<p>If you think that Costco isn't ruthless, I think you may be buying into an image, not a reality. Do you think that Costco borrowing billions of dollars just to pay out big dividends to shareholders before the end of 2012 in anticipation of higher tax rates in 2013 on was "pure"? It's good business (all publicly traded corporations answer, within the law and contracts they enter into, only to their shareholders - not their customers or their employees), but it's not particularly "community minded". For reasons like this, I don't just assume that Costco's motives are "pure" without evidence supporting that.</p>
<p>Yes, Costco benefits from having smarter employees and paying them a bit more while requiring them to be very flexible and not constrained by contract imposed constraints (such as those that would prevent a checker from being assigned to unload a truck). But, labor is just a smaller part of their equation than it is for "classic" Walmart stores so the cost is not as important.</p>
<p>For some random differences: Costco has NO 24 hour stores. Costco has a higher income consumer. Costco has larger packages which are harder to steal. Costco isn't trying to be a full service retailer by any stretch of the imagination. Costco has more control over their customers because their customers, by agreeing to terms of membership, have contractually agreed to some things (like checking contents of carts at the door which a regular retail outlet, at least in the state I live in, can only "ask" to do).</p>
<p>Yes, I hate shopping at Walmart the few time's I've done it. I wish they would hire trainable employees and train them better, but that's not their model. It may be biting their ass now with stocking problems in some stores and I am humored by that.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:48607">WillR</a> on <a href="/comments/1201068/49898742#c37">Sun Apr 14, 2013 at 12:09:49 AM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c36">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


	<ul id="k49898742" class="cm i1">




<li id="c38">
  <div class="cx" id="cx49903721">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">I started out simply saying that</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1201068/49903721#c38?mode=alone;showrate=1#c38">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Costco's CEO advocated raising the minimum wage. &nbsp;You and another poster seemed to think that was some kind of naivety on my part. And then you complain I'm argumentative when I point out I don't really care why they do it, but just that they do.</p>
<p>That's been largely my point. You could have left it alone a few posts ago, but you insisted on trying to prove to me that they're really ravening wolves - I'm suggesting by their fruits ye shall know them.</p>
<p>Once again, I don't care if Costco is ruthless, if they meet what I consider are their responsibilities to their employees, customers and community (they have a good environmental record too, from the little I've read, in addition to providing good paying jobs). They have no responsibility to not be ruthless with respect to their competitors, and in fact <i>vis a vis</i> someone like the Walton family, that would be one more plus IMO. I don't plan to marry Jim Sinegal (even though it would be legal in WA) - I just shop at his store.</p>
<p>They sell Koch Brothers paper products, which I don't buy (Fred Meyer/Kroger is cheaper anyway), and they're responsible for substantially increasing the cost of hard liquor here (which I also don't buy from them). I can get eggs for nearly 30 cents a dozen less from my local grocer, who also treats his employees well, or orange juice cheaper from Safeway, which is UFCW. But on balance, I feel good shopping there both because I save a substantial amount on food, and because I'm more in agreement with the company and its practices than in disagreement.</p>
<p>It's not like their CEO is as big an asshole as the CEO of Whole Foods, even if he's a ruthless competitor.</p>
<p>As to my former employer, it was a successful enough business model that I made out nicely on company stock when the company was acquired by a competitor. By then the founder wasn't much involved in the business beyond being a major stockholder (it was a long while after I left - too much travel with a kid at home; my wife, who worked there too, and I have run a similar business from home for 26 years - on a slightly smaller scale), and it was the then current management who negotiated the sale. &nbsp;People I knew who were still there made out pretty well in employment terms too - there weren't any mass layoffs due to consolidation.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig">
No matter how cynical you become, it's never enough to keep up - Lily Tomlin
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:6841">badger</a> on <a href="/comments/1201068/49903721#c38">Sun Apr 14, 2013 at 02:44:52 PM PDT</a></p>
